  "prompt": "Does my duck have hypothermia?",
  "response": "I'm not a veterinarian, but I can offer some general information that might help. Hypothermia in ducks can occur when they're exposed to cold temperatures for extended periods, especially if they don't have adequate shelter or protection from the elements. Signs of hypothermia in ducks may include:\n\n- **Shivering or trembling:** Ducks may shiver to generate heat.\n- **Lethargy:** Reduced activity levels and reluctance to move.\n- **Fluffed feathers:** Ducks might fluff up their feathers to trap more air and retain heat.\n- **Huddling:** Seeking warmth by staying close to other ducks or objects.\n- **Difficulty flying or walking:** Impaired coordination due to low body temperature.\n- **Pale or discolored skin:** Cooler body temperatures can affect coloration.\n\nIf you suspect your duck is experiencing hypothermia, it's important to take immediate action:\n\n1. **Provide Warmth:** Move the duck to a warmer, sheltered area. You can use blankets or towels to help retain body heat, but ensure they're not too tight or causing overheating.\n2. **Limit Stress:** Keep the environment calm to reduce stress, which can exacerbate health issues.\n3. **Hydration:** Ensure the duck has access to clean, unfrozen water.\n4. **Consult a Veterinarian:** Reach out to a qualified avian veterinarian as soon as possible for professional advice and treatment.\n\nEarly intervention is crucial to prevent more severe complications. Please contact a veterinary professional to get tailored advice and care for your duck.",
